ce:section.ce:para:
To analyze the morphological features of the catalysts and the elemental distribution of PdCo nanoparticles (NPs) on NCDs, TEM characterization and energy dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDX) were conducted on Pd/NCDs and Pd9Co1/NCDs. Fig. 2d and e present the TEM images of the synthesized Pd9Co1/NCDs catalyst, revealing that during the reduction process of PdCo, the NCDs underwent cross-linking to form nano-sheet structures similar to graphene [33–35]. These cross-linked NCDs uniformly encapsulate the reduced PdCo NPs. Importantly, due to the restraining effect exerted by cross-linked NCDs, no significant aggregation of the PdCo particles, which had an APS of 2.7 nm, was observed. The mean diameter of Pd NPs in Pd/NCDs was measured to be 3.2 nm (
                           Fig. S1
                        ), indicating that the addition of Co contributed to the formation of smaller metal NPs [26], thus enhancing the overall catalytic efficiency of the catalyst.

Without any regeneration treatment, the recoverability of the catalyst was investigated. The catalytic performance of Pd9Co1/NCDs exhibited a slight decline after five cycles (Fig. 4
                        i). After completing the cycle, Pd9Co1/NCDs catalyst recovered through centrifugation was washed, dried, and then characterized by XRD and TEM methods to determine structure and morphology. Compared with the fresh catalyst, the used Pd9Co1/NCDs catalyst (
                           Fig. S7
                        ) showed no obvious differences in the XRD spectrum. The slightly elevated peak intensities and narrower half-widths observed in the XRD pattern suggested an increase in the size of PdCo particles, reflecting an increase in the size of Pd NPs during the reaction. After completing the cyclic testing, the TEM image of Pd9Co1/NCDs (
                           Fig. S8
                        ) demonstrated that the uniform distribution of PdCo particles was preserved, while the APS increased from 2.7 nm to 3.0 nm, which observation aligned with the XRD results. Furthermore, both the film behavior of NCDs and the cross-linked architecture between NCDs and PdCo particles remained intact. The EDX elemental mapping of Pd9Co1/NCDs after the cycling experiment revealed an even distribution of Pd, Co, C, O, and N.
